snippet.textDisplay:
While I agree with nearly everything you said (and I'm not a Star Wars debater, enjoy them, dislike them, or hate them, everyone gets to have a valid opinion because Star Wars is different for everyone) I want to say that I think Rise is as good as it can be, with what was set up by TLJ. I didn't know how they'd come back to anything after TLJ destroyed whatever vision JJ had, but he did the best he could with what was handed back to him. As an ending to the sequel trilogy, it was about as good as I could have hoped for. I grew up with the OT, so I'll always love those the most, but I think (at this point, this could change) I'd rank the sequel trilogy higher than the prequel trilogy. The sequels had higher highs, and not as low of lows as the PT, and even though it didn't go exactly where I'd want it to, I'm not a creator, I don't get a say. I get to sit back, watch, and feel how I want to feel about what is presented.

So yes, good review, as always, we just disagree a bit where for you, this crushed your hope, and for me, it rejuvenated it a bit.

snippet.textDisplay:
Politics and personal egos destroyed the sequel trilogy.
The original trilogy was Lucas and a pool of like minded talented creatives working towards a common goal.
The prequels were George Lucas's singular focused vision.
The sequels were made by suits and creatives who clashed and compromised right to the bitter end. The fact that the final cut of Rise of Skywalker is a compromised cut that none of the people involved were completely happy with illustrates everything wrong with the creative process of the sequel trilogy.

Palpitine was a joke the fights were generic besides Kylo. Kylo honestly carried this movie for me. This movie was straight deus ex machina on repeat and I honestly wish I could explain every issue I had with this movie as a non Star Wars fan without having to write a full lengthed essay. The start of the movie had me regretting not watching Star Wars all my life and I planned on watching every movie but towards the end of the movie I just wanted my time and money back. The movie wasn’t terrible but it was severely disappointing.

snippet.textDisplay: This past week has just been a jumbled mess of trying to decide a full perspective on the Star Wars movies. The Star Wars movies have potential to be so so good, and every once in a while you can get enveloped in the full glory of the franchise, but I’m tired of seeing wasted potential for this series. It needs a new start with a quality road map, and established lore. Idk how they’d do this, maybe just go a couple fucking centuries in the future, but as long as we can latch onto a new quality arc of a Jedi fighting Sith with actual arcs that don’t lazily piggyback off tons of movies before it. The game they’re currently playing has to end, and we need to go back to when Star Wars was an isolated plot that compelled viewers into forming new bonds with characters that are bound by an awesome galaxy and lore.

snippet.textDisplay: In movies with many episodes, there is often one that ruins everything. In the case of "Star Wars" it is Episode 7. Many multi-part films were destroyed by a poorly made episode.  For example: "Alien 3", "Terminator 3", "Die Hard 5".  In my opinion, the episode 7 of the "Star Wars" should look different. Episode 7 should show how the Empire (Ok New Order) is reborn. The first parts represented the dark side of the power as it operated from cover and contributed to the creation of the empire. Episodes 4,5,6 show the domination and fall of the empire. But in Part 7, the stronger Death Star suddenly appears with the New Order. A resistance movement attack the death star, without any plan and preparation. They attack spontaneously. The complete opposite of an attack on the Death Star from episode 4 or 6. One question. Where did the "art of war" go?

snippet.textDisplay:
So many comments! 0_0
But DUDE!!!! My thoughts EXACTLY!!! You said all the things I thought and couldn't quite put into words, as I just came from the theater seeing it for the first time. I don't hate this movie, nor the trilogy as a whole. I actually liked TFA and LJ, but this being the 3rd movie... just didn't do it for me as a whole.
Disney should have had a plan from the beginning. I look at the MCU and how I felt during and after Endgame and then compare it to this... I freaking LOVED Endgame! But this... ugh.
I think my favorite thing about this movie was Ben being redeemed but still dying. Like you said, though, I did not like the kiss. I also liked Po and Finn doing more and this movie being more of a "them, together" story. I also enjoyed going, "Fringilla!!! Whatchoo doing here??? You're supposed to be wrecking The Continent!" XD XD XD XD XD

snippet.textDisplay: ⭐⭐⭐ The problem with this sequel trilogy is .... Twitter, Instagram, Facebook, social media, opinions, stacked on opinions stacked upon even more opinions! So many fanboys have to chime in on what THEY think should or should not happen in these movies. (If these fanboys have a problem, they should get together and make their own movie.) But they make enough noise to the point that Disney starts listening and starts worrying about losing $$$ due to negative reaction. As a result they waiver back and forth from movie to movie. There can never be a consistently good product if the director doesn't have the guts to stick to a good story because they're worried about the nerd backlash or not making enough $$$.

snippet.textDisplay:
Kathleen Kennedy = PROBLEM

She should have had JJ Abrams oversee the story and production of all three films in the same way that Jon Favreau had creative control over The Mandalorian ... that would have provoked greater continuity throughout the trilogy than bringing in an entirely new voice (Rian Johnson) and allowing him carte blanche with the direction of the overarching story in spite of whatever Abrams had set up prior.

If she liked Johnson more as a creative entity, she should have given him his own separate one-off film or enlisted him to do a later trilogy.

snippet.textDisplay:
I feel like Abrams went way too far in trying to correct the trilogy after the backlash directed at The Last Jedi. I felt like this movie pandered way too hard to those people, retconning everything die-hard fans didn't like and giving nothing but fan service at the expense of the trilogy. I think they should've had either one director or one producer overseeing everything, and stuck with one of the visions. We could've had two great trilogies, but instead we got two good movies and one mediocre one that don't mesh at all.


But, that's just my opinion.

snippet.textDisplay:
The reason why Rey’s character wasn’t developed as well as it should’ve been, is because Hollywood feminists don’t know how to write female characters with any depth. For them, their being female should suffice, should automatically make them compelling enough. Making Rey struggle in any real sense would thus be seen as sexist to them, which is why they flippantly referred to any criticism of Rey as being de facto sexist.

It ultimately shows how shallow their worldview is, as they develop such shallow characters, and are also so utterly incapable of conducting themselves rationally in any dialogue with their detractors.
